1. THE TASK BOARD
==============================================================

This is the Trello-style board. Three columns — To Do, In Progress,
Done. You can add tasks, edit them, drag them around, comment, and
look at the activity history.


### Creating, editing, and deleting tasks

What it is: the basics. Tap the plus button, fill in a title and a
description, hit save. You can make text **bold** or *italic* in the
description by selecting it and tapping the formatting buttons — under
the hood it just wraps the text with markdown markers, which we render
back as styled text when the card displays.

Where to find it:
  task_board_controller.dart:56  (createTask)
  task_board_controller.dart:80  (editTask)
  task_board_controller.dart:146 (deleteTask)
  widgets/rich_text.dart         (the bold/italic editor + parser)

Demo: Hit the plus button. Type a title. Type a description and use
the bold/italic toolbar. Save. The card appears at the top of To Do
instantly. Tap it again — there's already an entry in the activity
feed saying "Task created."

What to say if asked: "Rich text without a heavy library. The
description supports bold and italic via markdown markers, parsed
with one regex. I considered flutter_quill but it would have been
bigger than the rest of the feature combined."


### The drag-and-drop

This is the most interesting part of the task board. When you long-
press a card, three things happen at once:

  - Your phone vibrates a little (a "haptic")
  - The card lifts up off the page with a shadow underneath
  - It tilts slightly, like a real piece of paper being picked up

Then while you drag, you'll see:

  - The card you grabbed turns ghostly where it used to be
  - A blue rectangle opens up between cards to show where the new
    card will land if you let go
  - If you drag near the bottom of a column, the column scrolls to
    let you reach more cards
  - On a phone, if you drag near the edge of the screen, the whole
    board scrolls horizontally
  - On a phone, when you drop on a different column, that column
    smoothly slides into the centre of your screen so you can see
    where the card landed

When you let go, the ghost glides into its final position with a
little animation. If you let go outside any column (off-screen, or
in dead space), the ghost flies back to where it came from and
nothing changes.

I did NOT use Flutter's built-in drag widget for this. Flutter has
something called `Draggable` and `DragTarget`, but they're missing
shadows, edge-scrolling, and haptics. Building it from scratch was
a few hundred lines of code but every bit of it was needed.

Where to find it:
  drag/drag_controller.dart  — the brain of the gesture (state,
                                pointer tracking, where to drop)
  drag/drag_overlay.dart      — the floating ghost that follows
                                your finger
  widgets/task_card.dart      — wires the long-press gesture to
                                the controller
  widgets/task_column.dart    — the animated drop-slot indicator

Specific lines worth knowing:
  start (when long-press fires):                  drag_controller.dart:96
  the snap-into-place drop:                       drag_controller.dart:128
  the snap-back-to-source cancel:                 drag_controller.dart:164
  edge auto-scroll:                               drag_controller.dart:273
  centre-the-destination-column animation:        drag_controller.dart:152
  drop slot indicator that opens between cards:   widgets/task_column.dart:213

Demo: long-press a card in To Do. Drag it across to In Progress.
Notice the destination column slides into centre as you drop.
Drag another card and let go off-screen — it snaps back. Drag near
the bottom of a long column — it auto-scrolls.

What to say if asked: "Flutter ships a built-in drag widget but it
can't do shadows, edge auto-scroll, or haptics. I built a custom
gesture engine — long-press starts a state machine, the ghost lives
in a Stack overlay above the board, and a Ticker drives the auto-
scroll so the speed is consistent on 60Hz and 120Hz screens."


### The dropdown / drop-slot animation

When you drag a card, you see a blue rectangle open up between the
other cards to show where it'll land. That rectangle isn't fake —
it's a real animated widget that opens or collapses based on where
your finger is.

Where:  widgets/task_column.dart:213 (the _DropSlot widget)

This is one of the moments where Flutter's animation system shines.
The slot uses `AnimatedContainer` — give it a different height, it
animates to that height. We pair it with a `Selector` (a way to
listen to ONLY a piece of state instead of the whole controller) so
each slot only redraws when its own situation changes, not on every
finger movement.


### Comments and activity history

Each task keeps a list of comments and a list of audit entries (we
call them "activity entries"). Anything that happens to a task —
created, edited, moved between columns, priority changed, comment
added — appends an entry. The activity feed in the detail sheet
shows them newest-first.

Where:  task.dart (Comment, ActivityEntry types)
        task_board_controller.dart (every method that mutates a
        task appends an activity entry)

Demo: open a task. Type a comment, hit send. Watch it appear in the
list. Below that, the activity feed shows "X commented" plus all
the previous events.


### One technical thing worth knowing — modal sheets and providers

This sounds boring but it bit us hard. When you tap a card to open
its details, that opens a "modal bottom sheet" — a screen that
slides up from the bottom. The catch: Flutter pushes those sheets
into a different "container" in the widget tree, and they can't
see the data we set up at the screen level.

The fix is short but important: every sheet's `show()` method
captures the controller from the calling code and re-provides it
inside the sheet. If you ever add a new sheet, do the same.

Where every sheet does this trick:
  task_editor_sheet.dart:14
  task_detail_sheet.dart:15
  upload_sheet.dart:13
  document_detail_sheet.dart:15
  document_camera_screen.dart:43

If asked: "Modal routes are pushed under the root navigator, so
they're outside the screen-level provider scope. Every sheet
captures the controller from its calling context and re-provides
it. Same trick across all five sheets."


