2. THE DOCUMENT FEATURE
==============================================================

This is the second tab — KYC document verification. The user uploads
an ID/passport/utility bill, the "server" verifies it, and the user
sees the result.

We don't have a real server. We have a fake one called
MockDocumentBackend. It mimics what a real backend would do: returns
a document id from upload, then sends progress updates over a
WebSocket as it "processes" the document, and finally either approves
or rejects it.


### How an upload feels

When you pick a document:

  - The card appears in your list immediately, with a spinner saying
    "Uploading"
  - A few seconds later, the spinner becomes a progress bar, and the
    text changes to "Processing — Optical character recognition"
  - The progress bar moves through three stages: OCR, then field
    extraction, then authenticity check
  - About 12 seconds in, the document ends up Verified (green) or
    Rejected (red, with a reason)

This whole flow is designed to feel fast even though the network
"call" takes 900ms. We use something called an "optimistic update":
we add the card to the list BEFORE the network call returns. If the
call fails, we roll the card back to a "queued" state with a retry
button — the bytes stick around so you don't have to re-pick the file.

Where:
  upload (with the rollback):    document_repository_impl.dart:159
  the fake backend:               mock_document_backend.dart
  the three stages:               mock_document_backend.dart:158
  rejection messages list:        mock_document_backend.dart:240

Demo: tap +, pick a type, pick a source. Watch the card race through
the stages. Most of the time it'll end up Verified. About 1 in 4
will be Rejected (we set the rate to 0.25). If you want to demo the
rejection flow specifically, you can change `rejectionRate: 0.25`
to `rejectionRate: 1.0` in `MockDocumentBackend()` so every upload
gets rejected, then back to 0 after.

If asked: "Optimistic upload — the card is in the list before the
HTTP call completes, so the user sees instant feedback. On failure
I roll back to a 'queued' state and keep the bytes attached so retry
doesn't ask the user to re-pick the file."


### The connection banner (real-time updates)

The document feature has its own banner at the top, separate from
the global offline banner. This one tracks the WebSocket connection
specifically. When the WebSocket drops (which we make happen every
~30 seconds for the demo, otherwise you'd never see the reconnect
logic actually run), you see "Reconnecting…" in orange, and then
when it comes back you see nothing — the banner just disappears.

While the WebSocket is offline, we fall back to polling — calling
the status endpoint every 4 seconds — so the UI keeps updating even
without real-time. When the WebSocket reconnects, polling stops.

Where:
  the WebSocket itself:          document_websocket_client.dart
  the simulated drops:           document_websocket_client.dart:77
  exponential backoff:           document_websocket_client.dart:95
  the polling fallback:          document_polling_service.dart
  the state machine that picks: document_repository_impl.dart:280
                                  (the _onConnectionChanged method)

Demo: just wait ~30 seconds during the recording. The banner will
show up automatically. You can also tap it to manually trigger a
reconnect within ~200ms.

If asked: "Two layers — WebSocket for live pushes when connected,
polling as a fallback when not. Both feed updates into the same
single piece of code so they can't drift apart on what 'verified'
means. WebSocket reconnect uses exponential backoff capped at 30
seconds: 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 30."


### What happens when you kill the app

Documents are saved to the device. Their pictures are NOT — files
can be megabytes and we don't want to bloat shared preferences. So
when you kill the app and relaunch, you'll see all your uploaded
documents in the list, but if any was mid-upload when you killed
the app, it shows up as "Queued" with a retry button.

Where:
  saving:    document_repository_impl.dart  (the _persist method)
  loading:   document_repository_impl.dart  (the _hydrate method)

Demo: upload a doc, wait for verified, kill the app, relaunch. Doc
is still there.


