3. THE SECURITY STUFF (Day 2)
==============================================================

The brief weights "Security & Compliance" at 10% of the score. We
shipped five small features that put real code behind the security
story — not just paragraphs in the architecture doc.


### Secure storage (the device's safe)

What it is: a small wrapper around the operating system's built-in
"safe place." On iPhone it's called Keychain. On Android it's called
the AndroidKeyStore. Both are designed for storing sensitive values
that shouldn't be readable by other apps.

We use it to store two things right now:
  - A unique device id (we generate one on first run)
  - A signing key for the audit trail (more on that below)

In production we'd also put auth tokens and encryption keys here.
Today we don't have those yet, but the slot is built.

Where:
  core/secure_storage.dart  — the wrapper interface and platform impl

Demo (tricky to demo visually): upload a document, kill the app,
upload another. Both audit entries will have the same device id —
proving it survived the restart because it was in secure storage.

If asked: "Same `SecureStorage` interface that would hold auth
tokens or encryption keys in production. Currently it holds the
audit signing key and a per-device id."


### Audit signing (tamper-evident timeline)

Every entry in a document's audit timeline carries:
  - Who did it (you, or 'system')
  - From which device
  - The app version
  - A signature (HMAC) over the entry's contents
  - A "previous hash" — the hash of the previous entry's signature

That last bit is the tamper-evident chain. If someone edits an
entry after the fact, every later entry's signature stops matching.
An auditor can walk the chain and prove nothing was altered.

Where:
  the signing logic:        core/audit_signing.dart
  the chain construction:   document_repository_impl.dart  (the
                            _buildAudit method)
  the extended audit shape: document.dart  (the AuditEntry class)

Demo: open a document detail. The audit timeline shows multiple
entries. The cryptographic fields aren't visible in the UI — say
to the interviewer: "Each of these entries also carries a signature
and a hash of the previous entry. If anyone tampered with the log,
the chain would break. I built it the way KYC compliance auditors
expect to see it."

If asked: "Tamper-evident HMAC chain. Each entry signs over the
previous entry's signature, so any edit invalidates every later
entry's signature. An auditor verifies linearly."


### The biometric gate

Verified documents are protected behind Face ID / Touch ID / your
phone's fingerprint reader. Tapping a verified card triggers a
biometric prompt. If you pass, the detail sheet opens and the audit
log records "access granted via biometric." If you fail, you get a
snackbar saying access denied, and the audit log records the
denial.

If your phone has no biometric set up, we let access through but
log it as "no biometric available." This is intentional — soft-
locking a user out of their own data because their phone has no
fingerprint reader is the wrong tradeoff.

Where:
  the biometric wrapper:  core/biometrics.dart
  the gate itself:         document_dashboard_screen.dart:104
  Android prerequisite:   MainActivity.kt extends FlutterFragmentActivity
                          (otherwise the plugin throws a platform
                          exception)

Demo: tap a Verified card. Pass the biometric. Look at the audit —
new entry: "Access granted via biometric." Tap another verified
card, cancel the biometric, see the snackbar, see the new "Access
denied" audit entry.

If asked: "Real biometric prompt via local_auth. Works with Face ID
on iOS, BiometricPrompt on Android. The audit captures both
successful and failed attempts because compliance auditors care
about access patterns, not just successful access."


### Screenshot blocker (Android only, mostly)

When you're on the Documents tab, the app tells the operating system
"refuse any screenshot or screen recording attempts on this window."

  - On Android: it works. Try to take a screenshot, you'll get a
    system message saying "can't take screenshot due to security
    policy."
  - On iOS: Apple doesn't give us an API to block screenshots. The
    best we can do is detect when the user starts a screen recording
    and overlay a blur. That's what the code does on iOS, but you
    can't easily test it in the simulator.

When you switch back to the Tasks tab, normal screenshots work again
(reference-counted toggle).

Important: I temporarily disabled this for the video so I could
record. To re-enable for the final submission:
  1. In core/screen_capture_guard.dart, uncomment the body of
     `protect()` and remove the `return;` at the bottom.
  2. In app/home_shell.dart, remove the
     `ScreenProtector.protectDataLeakageOff()` line in initState.
  3. flutter clean && flutter run.

Where:
  the wrapper:    core/screen_capture_guard.dart
  the trigger:    app/home_shell.dart  (_syncScreenGuardFor)

If asked: "Reference-counted screen guard. On Android it sets
FLAG_SECURE; on iOS we use the screen_protector package's
detection-and-blur approach because Apple doesn't expose
screenshot blocking."


### The offline banner

A red banner at the top of the screen that appears when your phone
loses all network connections (Wi-Fi off AND cellular off). It
disappears as soon as connectivity comes back. Different from the
WebSocket banner — that one tracks the SWAMP connection
specifically; this one tracks the device's network state in
general.

Where:
  the watcher:    core/connectivity_state.dart
  the banner UI:  app/home_shell.dart  (_OfflineBanner)

Demo: turn on airplane mode. Banner appears. Turn it off. Banner
disappears.

If asked: "The connectivity_plus package tells us when there's no
adapter active. It doesn't guarantee the SWAMP server is reachable —
DNS or captive portals could still block traffic. For a stronger
signal we'd combine this with periodic API probes."


