4. THE BONUS FEATURES (Day 3)
==============================================================

The brief lists seven "bonus" features that get extra credit if
implemented. We did four of them. Each adds something visible to
the demo.


### OCR — reading text out of images

After you upload a document image, we run on-device text recognition
on it (using Google's free ML Kit). The recognized text shows up in
the document detail sheet two ways:

  - Each block of recognized text becomes a tappable rectangle
    overlaid on the image. Tap any rectangle to copy that text.
  - We also try to extract specific fields (Surname, Date of Birth,
    Document Number, Expiry) using regex patterns. If the image is
    a typical KYC document with those labels printed on it, you'll
    see chips at the top of the detail sheet showing the extracted
    values.

If you upload a photo of yourself, the chips won't appear because
your face doesn't say "Surname:" anywhere. That's correct behaviour —
the chips are targeted at standard KYC document layouts. The
tap-to-copy overlays still work on any text in any image.

Where:
  the OCR types:        domain/entities/document.dart:182  (OcrResult, OcrTextBlock)
  the OCR service:      data/ocr_service.dart
  the field extractor:  data/ocr_service.dart:131 (the regex set)
  wired into upload:    document_dashboard_controller.dart  (_enrichWithOcr)

Demo: upload a "specimen passport" image (search Google Images for
that). Open the detail. Chips appear at the top: Surname, Given
names, DOB. Pinch-zoom on the preview. Tap any text rectangle —
copies to clipboard, snackbar confirms.

If asked why this dependency: "On-device for privacy and cost. KYC
images shouldn't leave the device for cloud OCR. Cloud Vision API
costs per call. ML Kit is free at any scale, runs offline, has a
maintained Flutter package. I considered Tesseract but it's older
and more setup pain."


### Isolates — heavy work off the main thread

Some operations in the app are CPU-heavy and would otherwise freeze
the UI for ~50-100 milliseconds. We push those into "isolates" —
which is Dart's name for separate worker threads.

What runs in isolates:
  - Generating thumbnails (decoding the image, resizing, re-
    encoding as JPEG)
  - Computing the file checksum (a non-cryptographic hash over the
    bytes)
  - Running the OCR field-extraction regex pass

Without this, picking a 5MB photo would freeze the app for almost
a second while the checksum is computed. With it, the UI keeps
animating smoothly and the result arrives a moment later via a
future.

Where:
  the isolate wrappers:  core/image_processor.dart
                          (thumbnail, checksum, imageSize)
  used by the picker:    data/document_source.dart  (calls
                          ImageProcessor.checksum)
  used in the OCR path:  data/ocr_service.dart:99 (Isolate.run for
                          field extraction)

Demo: this is invisible by design. If you want to demonstrate it,
record the app in profile mode and show the DevTools timeline —
you'll see distinct isolate slices when picking a large photo.

If asked: "Compute-bound work that doesn't need the UI thread.
Isolate.run ships the bytes to a fresh isolate, runs the work,
returns the result. The calling code awaits asynchronously so the
UI keeps rendering frames during the work."


### The custom render object — for the document preview

When you open a verified document's detail, you see a preview area
with the document image and colored rectangles drawn over each
recognized text block. That preview area is built with what Flutter
calls a "custom render object" — that means we wrote our own
low-level widget instead of composing existing ones.

Why? Because we needed two things at the same time:
  - Custom drawing (the image plus the text-block overlays)
  - Custom touch handling (tapping a rectangle copies its text;
    pinching anywhere zooms; dragging anywhere pans)

Flutter's regular CustomPainter can do the drawing but can't help
with hit-testing. A real RenderBox can do both, sharing one
coordinate system between paint and tap detection.

Where:
  widgets/document_preview.dart
  - the public widget:           line 41 (DocumentPreview)
  - the render object proper:    line 184 (_RenderDocumentPreview)
  - the paint method:             line 263
  - the hit-test (which block was tapped): line 336
  - pinch and pan recognisers:   line 197

Demo: open a verified document's detail. The preview at the top
shows your document with overlay rectangles on every recognized
word. Pinch to zoom. Pan around. Tap any rectangle — the text gets
copied to your clipboard, the rectangle highlights, snackbar confirms.

If asked: "I needed both custom paint AND block-aware hit testing.
A CustomPainter wrapped in a GestureDetector would only know that
SOMETHING in the area was tapped, not which text block. Writing a
real RenderBox lets paint and hit-test share the same coordinates
so taps map back to specific blocks."


### Custom camera — real-time edge detection

If you tap "Scan with custom camera" in the upload sheet, you get a
full-screen scanner instead of the system camera. Live preview, with
green corner brackets that animate to follow the edges of whatever
document you point at. A pill at the top tells you "Document
detected" when confidence is high. Tap the capture button to take
the shot.

The edge detection is real — we sample camera frames at about 6
times per second, compute gradients, and find the strongest
horizontal and vertical edges. That's the document's likely
bounding box. We map that back to screen coordinates and the
corner brackets animate there.

Where:
  the edge detection algorithm:  core/edge_detection.dart
  the camera screen:              sheets/document_camera_screen.dart
  the scanner overlay paint:      document_camera_screen.dart:297

Demo: tap +, pick a type, tap "Scan with custom camera." Aim at any
printed page. Watch the corner brackets snap to the page edges.
Capture.

If asked: "Sobel-style gradient on the camera's luma plane,
downsampled to 160 pixels wide for speed. Find dominant horizontal
and vertical edges, pick two well-separated peaks per axis, that's
the document's bounding rect. Not a four-corner perspective fit —
that would need Hough lines and a corner solver, out of scope."


