5. HOW THE PROJECT IS LAID OUT
==============================================================

  lib/
  ├── app/                      ← navigation shell (the bottom nav)
  ├── core/                     ← shared utilities used by both features
  ├── features/
  │   ├── task_board/
  │   │   ├── data/             ← in-memory storage
  │   │   ├── domain/           ← what a Task is, abstract storage interface
  │   │   └── presentation/     ← screen, controller, drag, widgets, sheets
  │   └── document_verification/
  │       ├── data/             ← mock backend, websocket, polling, repo
  │       ├── domain/           ← what a Document is, abstract repo interface
  │       └── presentation/     ← screen, controller, widgets, sheets
  ├── home.dart
  └── main.dart

The most important rule: the two features in `lib/features/` import
nothing from each other. Both share only `lib/core/`. That's how we
answer the brief's question about scaling to a 4-developer team —
two teams own one feature each, with `core/` as their only shared
dependency.

Inside each feature, the rule is similar: presentation talks to
abstract interfaces in domain. The concrete data implementations
are wired in just one place (the screen's initState). That means
swapping in a real database later is a one-line change, not a
rewrite.


