7. THE QUESTIONS YOU'LL ACTUALLY GET ASKED
==============================================================

I've grouped these by likely first question. For each one, the
short answer first (read this aloud), then a follow-up only if
they push.


### "Walk me through the architecture."

Short answer: Two features under lib/features/ — tasks and
documents. They share only lib/core/. Inside each feature, three
folders: domain (the data shapes), data (the storage implementation),
presentation (the UI). The widgets only ever talk to the controller;
the controller only ever talks to the abstract repository in
domain/. The concrete repository is wired in once, at the screen
level. Swapping to a real database later is a one-line change.

If pushed: walk through one feature path top to bottom — "when
you tap upload, here's exactly what happens" — using the document
feature.


### "Why provider, not Bloc or Riverpod?"

Short answer: For one screen per feature with no cross-screen
state, Bloc would push me to write event classes for every CRUD
call — boilerplate that doesn't earn its keep. Riverpod's
compile-time DI is nice, but the dependency graph here is small
enough to read directly in the screen's initState. Provider got
me what I needed with less ceremony.

If pushed: "The architecture isn't tied to provider. The
controllers are just ChangeNotifiers — I could swap them for
Cubits or Notifiers without rewriting the business logic."


### "Why a custom drag and drop?"

Short answer: Flutter ships a Draggable widget but it can't do
shadow previews, can't auto-scroll when you drag near an edge,
and doesn't trigger haptics. The brief asked for all three. So
I built a custom gesture engine with a state machine, a Stack-
level overlay for the floating ghost, and a Ticker for frame-
locked auto-scroll.

If pushed about the state machine: "Four states — idle, dragging,
dropping, cancelling. The transitions are explicit. Secondary
long-presses during a drop animation are rejected; pointer cancel
mid-drag triggers the snap-back-to-source path."


### "Why on-device OCR specifically?"

Short answer: Three reasons. Privacy — KYC images shouldn't leave
the device for a cloud OCR pass. Cost — ML Kit is free at any
volume; Cloud Vision charges per call. Latency — no network
roundtrip during the upload flow.

If pushed about alternatives: "Considered Tesseract via FFI —
older, slower setup. Apple Vision is iOS only. Cloud Vision was
ruled out for the reasons above. ML Kit is the standard mobile
on-device choice."


### "Why isolates here?"

Short answer: Three pieces of work — generating thumbnails,
computing file checksums, OCR field extraction — are CPU-bound
and don't need the UI thread. On a 10MB image they'd block the
UI for 50-100ms. Isolate.run pushes them to a separate worker
thread so the UI keeps animating.

If pushed: "Specifically the operations in
core/image_processor.dart and the field-extractor regex pass
inside ocr_service.dart at line 99. The native ML Kit text
recognition itself already runs on its own native thread, so
that doesn't need an isolate — but the post-processing does."


### "Why did you write a custom render object?"

Short answer: The document preview needs both custom drawing
(image plus text-block overlays) AND custom hit-testing (taps map
back to specific text blocks). A CustomPainter wrapped in a
GestureDetector would only know that SOMETHING in the area was
tapped, not which block. Writing a real RenderBox lets paint and
hit-test share one coordinate system.

If pushed: "It's in widgets/document_preview.dart at line 184. The
gestures are also handled in the render object itself — a
ScaleGestureRecognizer for pinch and pan, a TapGestureRecognizer
for block-aware taps. The widget tree above this is one line."


### "How would you swap in a real database?"

Short answer: TaskRepository and DocumentRepository are abstract
interfaces in domain/. I'd add a new file like
data/drift_task_repository.dart that implements the same
interface, change one line in the screen's initState from
`InMemoryTaskRepository()` to `DriftTaskRepository(db)`, and the
controllers, widgets, and sheets all keep working unchanged.

If pushed about Drift specifically: "I'd pick Drift over Isar.
Isar is faster but its maintenance momentum has wobbled lately
and for a long-lived KYC product I want the conservative bet.
Drift has the same SQLite engine with a typed code-generated API
and reactive query streams — that last one matters because we
want 'tell me when this list changes' subscriptions, not 'fetch
me a snapshot' calls."


### "What about state persistence?"

Short answer: Documents persist as JSON in SharedPreferences. The
file bytes themselves are NOT persisted — they could be megabytes
each. On cold start, the hydrate logic walks the persisted list;
anything in 'uploading' state gets repaired to 'queued' with bytes
cleared, so the user is prompted to retry.

If pushed: "It's in document_repository_impl.dart in the _persist
and _hydrate methods. The repair logic is what makes the cold-start
flow feel sane — without it, a 'still uploading' card from before
the kill would have nowhere to recover."


### "What's tested?"

Short answer: 14 unit tests, all passing. Seven cover the
TaskBoardController — CRUD flows, the within-column index
off-by-one for drag reorder, comment + activity appends,
notification scheduling. Seven cover the document stack —
optimistic upload, rollback on failure, retry, persistence
round-trip, websocket reconnect cycle, polling tick emission, and
polling re-entry guard.

If pushed about widget tests: "Drag and gesture flows aren't unit-
tested because gesture timing in widget tests is fragile — that's
what the demo video covers. Integration tests with patrol would
be the next step."


==============================================================
8. WHAT WE DELIBERATELY DIDN'T BUILD
==============================================================

These are things the brief mentions but we chose not to build, with
the reasons. Senior interviewers like to ask about omissions. Be
ready.


### Real backend

The mock pipeline has the correct wire shapes — it returns the
exact JSON a real server would. Swapping in package:http for the
HTTP client and package:web_socket_channel for the WebSocket is a
class-per-client change, not a rewrite.

Why not built: the brief says explicitly "you do not need a live
backend — stub or mock the responses." So we did, well.


### Real local notifications

The NotificationService interface is in place — used today by the
task feature for due-date reminders. The implementation just logs
to the debug console. The real implementation would use
flutter_local_notifications.

Why not built: notifications need Android and iOS native config —
permission requests, app icons for the notification center, etc.
That's a couple hours of setup for a feature that wouldn't be
visible in the video.


### Real encryption-at-rest of document bytes

We talk about envelope encryption with AES-GCM in ARCHITECTURE.md.
The key-management primitives (secure storage, signing key) are in
place. AES-GCM via package:cryptography is described as the next
step.

Why not built: the bytes aren't persisted to disk in the first
place — they live in memory during upload and get cleared on cold
start. Encrypting them adds complexity without protecting against
any actual attacker we have today.


### CRDTs for offline task sync

The brief lists this as a bonus item: "implement Phase 4 instead
of writing it." We wrote Phase 4 (the offline section in
ARCHITECTURE.md describes Lamport timestamps with field-level
last-write-wins). Building real CRDTs is 15-20 hours of careful
work — done badly they're worse than not done at all.

Why not built: time/risk tradeoff. The written approach is
defensible and the implementation would have eaten a day with high
chance of subtle bugs.


### Direct platform-channel code

The brief's bonus list mentions "Platform channels for native
biometric or secure enclave integration." We use platform channels
already, just through plugins (local_auth, flutter_secure_storage,
image_picker). Rolling our own channel code from scratch would
add code surface without changing user-visible behaviour.

Why not built: redundant. Our security primitives already use
platform channels under the hood — we just don't write the channel
code by hand.


### GDPR endpoints (right to erasure, DSARs)

The brief mentions "production-ready data handling" and we cover
GDPR considerations in ARCHITECTURE.md. Building actual delete
flows and DSAR exports needs a real backend to delete from / export
out of.

Why not built: requires a real server. Architecture is shaped to
make this trivial when one exists.


==============================================================
9. THINGS THAT BIT US ON REAL DEVICES (already fixed)
==============================================================

This is your "I expected this to happen" cheat sheet. If anything
weird shows up while testing, check this list first.


### local_auth wants FlutterFragmentActivity, not FlutterActivity

Symptom: biometric prompt fails with PlatformException
("no_fragment_activity").

Cause: the local_auth plugin's BiometricPrompt code requires the
host activity to be a FragmentActivity. Flutter's default
FlutterActivity isn't.

Fix (already applied): MainActivity.kt extends
FlutterFragmentActivity. File:
  android/app/src/main/kotlin/com/example/untitled2/MainActivity.kt


### Image-picker camera kills the app on Android

Symptom: tap "Quick photo," camera launches, after capture either
black screen or full app restart.

Cause: when Android launches a camera intent, it can kill your
Flutter process to free memory. When the user comes back, your
process restarts cold and the original picker future never resolves.

Fix (already applied): largeHeap="true" in AndroidManifest, plus
retrieveLostData() recovery on the controller side. Files:
  android/app/src/main/AndroidManifest.xml
  document_source.dart
  document_dashboard_controller.dart

For the demo, prefer "Scan with custom camera." It's in-process
and doesn't have this class of problem.


### OCR field-chips don't appear on a selfie

Symptom: you uploaded a photo of yourself and expected to see
Surname / DOB chips. None appeared.

Cause: the chips only appear when the regex pass finds literal
KYC labels ("Surname:", "DOB:", etc.) in the recognized text. A
selfie doesn't contain those labels, so no chips.

Workaround: upload a specimen passport image or a printed page
that contains those labels.

Reality check: tap-to-copy on text overlays IS the OCR working —
the chips are an extra heuristic on top.


### iOS Simulator is unreliable for ML Kit

Symptom: OCR results sparse or missing.

Cause: ML Kit's iOS implementation has setup quirks the simulator
sometimes doesn't satisfy.

Fix: test OCR on a real iPhone. Everything else works in the
simulator.


### iOS doesn't actually block screenshots

Symptom: you screenshotted the Documents tab on iOS and the
screenshot worked.

Cause: Apple gives no API to block screenshots. The screen-protector
package on iOS only does blur on screen-recording detection.

Fix: nothing we can do — platform limitation. Be honest about it
in the interview.


